:::summary
*The Silmarillion* is J.R.R. Tolkien's mythological history of Middle-earth, published posthumously in 1977 and edited by his son Christopher Tolkien. It encompasses the creation of the world, the fall of the angelic Ainur, the wars of the Elves against the Dark Lord Morgoth, and the ancient ages that gave rise to the world of *The Lord of the Rings*. For Tolkien, the work was a lifelong labor of love — a mythology he wished to give to England, saturated with themes of creation, fall, redemption, and the longing for the divine.
:::

